




TY  - JOUR
T1  - How Do Competitive Pressures Affect Incentives to Innovate When There Is a Market for Inventions?
AU  - Spulber, Daniel F.
Y1  - 2013/12/01
PY  - 2013
DA  - 2013/12/01
N1  - doi: 10.1086/674134
DO  - 10.1086/674134
T2  - Journal of Political Economy
JF  - Journal of Political Economy
SP  - 1007
EP  - 1054
VL  - 121
IS  - 6
PB  - The University of Chicago Press
N2  - Competition and intellectual property (IP) protections are complements in stimulating innovation. When IP is appropriable, a market for inventions forms and competitive pressures increase incentives to innovate. Competition among producers, the demand side of the market for inventions, and competition among inventors, the supply side of the market for inventions, create incentives to innovate. When IP is not fully appropriable, markets for inventions are limited and competitive pressures can decrease incentives to innovate. Firms vertically integrate R&D and production and share technology to appropriate the returns to IP. This implies that antitrust policy and IP protections are complements.
AB  - Competition and intellectual property (IP) protections are complements in stimulating innovation. When IP is appropriable, a market for inventions forms and competitive pressures increase incentives to innovate. Competition among producers, the demand side of the market for inventions, and competition among inventors, the supply side of the market for inventions, create incentives to innovate. When IP is not fully appropriable, markets for inventions are limited and competitive pressures can decrease incentives to innovate. Firms vertically integrate R&D and production and share technology to appropriate the returns to IP. This implies that antitrust policy and IP protections are complements.
SN  - 0022-3808
M3  - doi: 10.1086/674134
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1086/674134
Y2  - 2024/03/22
ER  - 

TY  - JOUR
T1  - Credit Shocks and Aggregate Fluctuations in an Economy with Production Heterogeneity
AU  - Khan, Aubhik
AU  - Thomas, Julia K.
Y1  - 2013/12/01
PY  - 2013
DA  - 2013/12/01
N1  - doi: 10.1086/674142
DO  - 10.1086/674142
T2  - Journal of Political Economy
JF  - Journal of Political Economy
SP  - 1055
EP  - 1107
VL  - 121
IS  - 6
PB  - The University of Chicago Press
N2  - We study the cyclical implications of credit market imperfections in a quantitative dynamic, stochastic general equilibrium model wherein firms face persistent shocks to aggregate and individual productivity. In our model economy, optimal capital reallocation is distorted by two frictions: collateralized borrowing and partial investment irreversibility. We find that a negative shock to borrowing conditions can, on its own, generate a large and persistent recession through disruptions to the distribution of capital. This recession, and the subsequent recovery, is distinguished both quantitatively and qualitatively from that driven by an exogenous shock to total factor productivity.
AB  - We study the cyclical implications of credit market imperfections in a quantitative dynamic, stochastic general equilibrium model wherein firms face persistent shocks to aggregate and individual productivity. In our model economy, optimal capital reallocation is distorted by two frictions: collateralized borrowing and partial investment irreversibility. We find that a negative shock to borrowing conditions can, on its own, generate a large and persistent recession through disruptions to the distribution of capital. This recession, and the subsequent recovery, is distinguished both quantitatively and qualitatively from that driven by an exogenous shock to total factor productivity.
SN  - 0022-3808
M3  - doi: 10.1086/674142
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1086/674142
Y2  - 2024/03/22
ER  - 

TY  - JOUR
T1  - The International Diversification Puzzle Is Not as Bad as You Think
AU  - Heathcote, Jonathan
AU  - Perri, Fabrizio
Y1  - 2013/12/01
PY  - 2013
DA  - 2013/12/01
N1  - doi: 10.1086/674143
DO  - 10.1086/674143
T2  - Journal of Political Economy
JF  - Journal of Political Economy
SP  - 1108
EP  - 1159
VL  - 121
IS  - 6
PB  - The University of Chicago Press
N2  - The international diversification puzzle is the fact that country portfolios are on average biased toward domestic assets, while one-good international macro models with nondiversifiable labor income risk predict the opposite pattern of diversification. This paper embeds a portfolio choice decision in a two-good international business cycle model and provides a closed-form solution for equilibrium country portfolios. Equilibrium portfolios are biased toward domestic assets because endogenous international relative price fluctuations make domestic assets a good hedge against labor income risk. Evidence from developed economies in recent years is qualitatively and quantitatively consistent with the mechanisms highlighted by the theory.
AB  - The international diversification puzzle is the fact that country portfolios are on average biased toward domestic assets, while one-good international macro models with nondiversifiable labor income risk predict the opposite pattern of diversification. This paper embeds a portfolio choice decision in a two-good international business cycle model and provides a closed-form solution for equilibrium country portfolios. Equilibrium portfolios are biased toward domestic assets because endogenous international relative price fluctuations make domestic assets a good hedge against labor income risk. Evidence from developed economies in recent years is qualitatively and quantitatively consistent with the mechanisms highlighted by the theory.
SN  - 0022-3808
M3  - doi: 10.1086/674143
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1086/674143
Y2  - 2024/03/22
ER  - 

TY  - JOUR
T1  - Taxation and Redistribution of Residual Income Inequality
AU  - Golosov, Mikhail
AU  - Maziero, Pricila
AU  - Menzio, Guido
Y1  - 2013/12/01
PY  - 2013
DA  - 2013/12/01
N1  - doi: 10.1086/674135
DO  - 10.1086/674135
T2  - Journal of Political Economy
JF  - Journal of Political Economy
SP  - 1160
EP  - 1204
VL  - 121
IS  - 6
PB  - The University of Chicago Press
N2  - This paper studies the optimal redistribution of income inequality caused by the presence of search and matching frictions in the labor market. We study this problem in the context of a directed search model of the labor market populated by homogeneous workers and heterogeneous firms. The optimal redistribution can be attained using a positive unemployment benefit and an increasing and regressive labor income tax. The positive unemployment benefit serves the purpose of lowering the search risk faced by workers. The increasing and regressive labor tax serves the purpose of aligning the cost to the firm of attracting an additional applicant with the value of an application to society.
AB  - This paper studies the optimal redistribution of income inequality caused by the presence of search and matching frictions in the labor market. We study this problem in the context of a directed search model of the labor market populated by homogeneous workers and heterogeneous firms. The optimal redistribution can be attained using a positive unemployment benefit and an increasing and regressive labor income tax. The positive unemployment benefit serves the purpose of lowering the search risk faced by workers. The increasing and regressive labor tax serves the purpose of aligning the cost to the firm of attracting an additional applicant with the value of an application to society.
SN  - 0022-3808
M3  - doi: 10.1086/674135
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1086/674135
Y2  - 2024/03/22
ER  - 

TY  - JOUR
T1  - Why Blame?
AU  - Gurdal, Mehmet Y.
AU  - Miller, Joshua B.
AU  - Rustichini, Aldo
Y1  - 2013/12/01
PY  - 2013
DA  - 2013/12/01
N1  - doi: 10.1086/674409
DO  - 10.1086/674409
T2  - Journal of Political Economy
JF  - Journal of Political Economy
SP  - 1205
EP  - 1247
VL  - 121
IS  - 6
PB  - The University of Chicago Press
N2  - We provide experimental evidence that subjects blame others on the basis of events they are not responsible for. In our experiment an agent chooses between a lottery and a safe asset; payment from the chosen option goes to a principal, who then decides how much to allocate between the agent and a third party. We observe widespread blame: regardless of their choice, agents are blamed by principals for the outcome of the lottery, an event they are not responsible for. We provide an explanation of this apparently irrational behavior with a delegated-expertise principal-agent model, the subjects? salient perturbation of the environment.
AB  - We provide experimental evidence that subjects blame others on the basis of events they are not responsible for. In our experiment an agent chooses between a lottery and a safe asset; payment from the chosen option goes to a principal, who then decides how much to allocate between the agent and a third party. We observe widespread blame: regardless of their choice, agents are blamed by principals for the outcome of the lottery, an event they are not responsible for. We provide an explanation of this apparently irrational behavior with a delegated-expertise principal-agent model, the subjects? salient perturbation of the environment.
SN  - 0022-3808
M3  - doi: 10.1086/674409
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1086/674409
Y2  - 2024/03/22
ER  - 

